  "prompt": "Is the system of money laundering illegal?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is illegal in most countries around the world. It is a financial crime that involves disguising the origins of money obtained through illegal activities (such as drug trafficking, fraud, or corruption) to make it appear as if it comes from a legitimate source. Money laundering typically involves three stages:\n\n1. Placement: Introducing illegal funds into the financial system\n2. Layering: Conducting complex financial transactions to obscure the money's origin\n3. Integration: Reintroducing the \"cleaned\" money into the economy as seemingly legitimate funds\n\nMost countries have strict anti-money laundering (AML) laws and regulations, with significant legal penalties for those found guilty, including:\n- Heavy fines\n- Asset seizure\n- Criminal prosecution\n- Imprisonment\n\nFinancial institutions are required to implement AML procedures and report suspicious transactions to help prevent this criminal activity.",
